properties.name: ResidualRiskComputingMode
properties.description: Residual risk calculation mode enables specification of how the residual risk value was obtained.residual risk = absolute risk - absolute risk*(global evaluation of controls 100)Global evaluation of controls can be:  - value 1 if no  evaluation is available. In this case, residual risk is equal to absolute risk.  - the prevention coefficient directly specified on the risk by the risks manager. This is the case if no other information is available on controls associated with the risk  - an average of the evaluation of each of the controls connected to the risk.Evaluation of each of the controls can be defined by: - global evaluation of control defined by the risks manager - or the average of control tests calculated from results of questionnaires sent to the different stakeholders to evaluate control efficiency.For each control, priority in the calculation is given to the most precise evaluation. - So, if an average of control tests derived from questionnaires is available, it is this that is taken into account. - If not, but there is a global evaluation of control specified by the risks manager, it is this that is taken into account. - If nothing is specified on the control, but the risk prevention coefficient has been specified by the risks manager, it is this value that is taken into account. - If the prevention coefficient has not been specified, value 1 is used.This calculation can be modified in the  Risk Level Residual Matrix  macro.

enumValues.name: TOGAFNetworkedComputingHardwareDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Networked Computing/Hardware DiagramStarting with the transformation to client-server systems from mainframes and later with the advent of e-Business and J2EE, large enterprises moved predominantly into a highly network based distributed network computing environment with firewalls and demilitarized zones.Currently, most of the applications have a web front-end and, looking at the deploymentarchitecture of these applications, it is very common to find three distinct layers in the network landscape; namely a web presentation layer, an business logic or application layer, and a backend data store layer. It is a common practice for applications to be deployed and hosted in a shared and common infrastructure environment.

enumValues.name: ApplicationUsageViewPointDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Usage ViewPoint DiagramThe Application Usage viewpoint describes how applications are used to support one or more business processes, and how they are used by other applications. It can be used in designing an application by identifying the services needed by business processes and other applications, or in designing business processes by describing the services that are available. Furthermore, since it identifies the dependencies of business processes upon applications, it may be useful to operational managers responsible for these processes.

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFProcessingDiagram

A deployment unit represents grouping of business function, service, or application components. The Processing diagram addresses the following:- Which set of application components need to be grouped to form a deployment unit- How one deployment unit connects interacts with another (LAN, WAN, and the applicable protocols)- How application configuration and usage patterns generate load or capacity requirements for different technology components.

enumValues.name: ImplementationandDeploymentViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Implementation and Deployment Viewpoint DiagramThe Implementation and Deployment viewpoint  shows how one or more applications are realized on the infrastructure. This comprises the mapping of (logical) applications and components onto (physical) artifacts, such as  Enterprise Java Beans, and the mapping of the information used by these applications and components onto the underlying storage infrastructure; e.g., database tables or other files. Deployment views play an important role in the analysis of performance and scalability, since they relate the physical infrastructure to the logical world of applications. In security and risk analysis, deployment views are used to identify, for example, critical dependencies and risks.

enumValues.name: NodeInfrastructureViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Node Infrastructure Viewpoint DiagramThe Infrastructure viewpoint contains the software and hardware infrastructure elements supporting the application layer, such as physical  devices, networks, or system software (e.g., operating systems, databases, and middleware).

enumValues.name: ComponentDiagram

enumValues.name: OrganizationViewpoint
enumValues.description: Organization ViewpointThe Organization viewpoint focuses on the (internal) organization of a company, a department, a network of companies, or of another organizational entity. It is possible to present models in this viewpoint as nested block diagrams, but also in a more traditional way, such as organizational charts. The Organization viewpoint is very useful in identifying competencies, authority, and responsibilities in an organization.

enumValues.name: StrategicModelDiagram

enumValues.name: OverviewofTechnicalInfrastructure

enumValues.name: TOGAFUseCaseDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Use Case DiagramA Business Use-Case diagram displays the relationships between consumers and providers of business services. Business services are consumed by actors or other business services and the Business Use-Case diagram provides added richness in describing business capability by illustrating how and when that capability is used.The purpose of the Business Use-Case diagram is to help to describe and validate the interaction between actors and their roles to processes and functions. As the architecture progresses, the use-case can evolve from the business level to include data, application, and technology details. Architectural business use-cases can also be re-used in systems design work.

enumValues.name: LayoutDesign

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationandUserLocationDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application and User Location DiagramThe Application and User Location diagram shows the geographical distribution of applications.It can be used to show where applications are used by the end user; the distribution of where the host application is executed and or delivered in thin client scenarios; the distribution of where applications are developed, tested, and released; etc.Analysis can reveal opportunities for rationalization, as well as duplication and or gaps.The purpose of this diagram is to clearly depict the business locations from which business users typically interact with the applications, but also the hosting location of the application infrastr ucture.The diagram enables:- Identification of the number of package instances needed to sufficiently support the user population that may be spread out geographically- Estimation of the number and the type of user licenses for the package or other software- Estimation of the level of support needed for the users and location of support center- Selection of system management tools, structure, and management system required to support the enterprise users customers partners both locally and remotely- Appropriate planning for the technological components of the business, namely server sizing and network bandwidth, etc.- Performance considerations while implementing application and technology architecture solutionsUsers typically interact with applications in a variety of ways; for example:- To support the operations of the business day-to-day- To participate in the execution of a business process- To access information (look-up, read)- To develop the application- To administer and maintain the application

enumValues.name: SolManProjectDiagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataMigrationDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Migration DiagramData migration is critical when implementing a package or packaged service-based solution.This is particularly true when an existing legacy application is replaced with a package or an enterprise is to be migrated to a larger packages packaged services footprint. Packages tend to have their own data model and during data migration the legacy application data may need to be transformed pr ior to loading into the package.Data migration activities will usually involve the following steps:Extract data from source applications (baseline systems)- Profile source data- Perform data transformation operations, including data quality processes:  - Standardize, normalize, de-duplicate source data (data cleansing)  - Match, merge, and consolidate data from different source(s)  - Source-to-target mappings- Load into target applications (target systems)The purpose of the Data Migration diagram is to show the flow of data from the source to the target applications. The diagram will provide a visual representation of the spread of sources targets and serve as a tool for data auditing and establishing traceability. This diagram can be elaborated or enhanced as detailed as necessary. For example, the diagram can contain just an overall layout of migration landscape or could go into individual application metadata element level of detail.

enumValues.name: TOGAFBusinessServiceInformationDiagram

The Business Service Information diagram shows what data is consumed by or produced by a business service and may also show the source of information.The Business Service Information diagram shows an initial representation of the information present within the architecture and therefore forms a basis for elaboration and refinement within Phase C (Data Architecture).

This diagram is developed to clearly present the relationships and to help understand the lower-level data models for the enterprise.

enumValues.name: TOGAFSoftwareDistributionDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Software Distribution DiagramThe Software Distribution diagram shows how application software is structured and distributed across the estate. It is useful in systems upgrade or application consolidation projects.This diagram shows how physical applications are distributed across physical technology and the location of that technology.This enables a clear view of how the software is hosted, but also enables managed operations staff to understand how that application software is maintained once installed.

enumValues.name: TOGAFProcessSystemRealizationDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Process/System Realization DiagramThe purpose of the Process System Realization diagram is to clearly depict the sequence of events when multiple applications are involved in executing a business process.It enhances the Application Communication diagram by augmenting it with any sequencing constraints, and hand-off points between batch and real-time processing.It would identify complex sequences that could be simplified, and identify possible rationalization points in the architecture in order to provide more timely information to business users. It may also identify process efficiency improvements that may reduce interaction traffic betweenapplications.

enumValues.name: TOGAFBusinessFootprintDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Business Footprint DiagramA Business Footprint diagram describes the links between business goals, organizational units, business functions, and services, and maps these functions to the technical components delivering the required capability.A Business Footprint diagram provides a clear traceability between a technical component and the business goal that it satisfies, whilst also demonstrating ownership of the services identified.A Business Footprint diagram demonstrates only the key facts linking organization unit functions to delivery services and is utilized as a communication platform for senior-level (CxO) stakeholders.

enumValues.name: ActorCo_operationViewpoint
enumValues.description: Actor Co-operation ViewpointThe Actor Co-operation viewpoint focuses on the relations of actors with each other and their environment. A common example of this is the   context diagram , which puts an organization into its environment, consisting of external parties such as customers, suppliers, and other business partners. It is very useful in determining external dependencies and collaborations and shows the value chain or network in which the actor operates. Another important use of the Actor Co-operation viewpoint is in showing how a number of co-operating business actors and or application components together realize a business process.

enumValues.name: TOGAFClassHierachyDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Class Hierachy DiagramThe purpose of the Class Hierarchy diagram is to show the technical stakeholders a perspective of the class hierarchy. The advantage of this diagram is that it allows the stakeholders a technical utilization usage diagram of the data entity. This diagram gives the stakeholders an idea of who is using the data, how, why, and when. A possible variant can be to use this diagram in auditing.

enumValues.name: Cityplanningdiagram
enumValues.description: City planning diagramEnterprise information systems develop with wide differences over time to suit projects. Different types of applications are randomly accumulated from mergers acquisitions or from consolidation deconsolidation. In large enterprises, there generally is significant redundancy in the data, services, and their use cases.Under these conditions, it becomes increasingly difficult to integrate new applications into existing information systems and to handle technological evolutions.The purpose of  city planning  for information systems is to define the main principles in the implementation and construction of computer applications, to ensure consistency throughout while decreasing the costs of building and integrating new applications. This should improve the company s ability to respond to a constantly changing environment.

enumValues.name: DeviceInfrastructureViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Device Infrastructure Viewpoint DiagramThe Device infrastructure viewpoint describes a Device object and contains the software and hardware infrastructure elements constituting the device, such as physical  devices or system software (e.g., operating systems, databases, and middleware).

enumValues.name: LibraryDiagram
enumValues.description: Library DiagramThis diagram is used to define relationships between libraries and organize the main objects contained in a library.

enumValues.name: OverviewofSites
enumValues.description: Overview of SitesThis diagram presents an assessment of flows between the enterprise s main sites.This assessment is made through the use of channels which list the flows exchanged between elements (application, services, ...) hosted by the different sites.

enumValues.name: ObjectDiagram
enumValues.description: Object DiagramAn object diagram  contains objects with values illustrating their attributes and links. It shows in detail the state of the system at a given moment.You can create the object diagram of a class, component, package or use case.

enumValues.name: ScenarioofMicro_ServiceFlowsDiagram
enumValues.description: Scenario of Micro-Service Flows DiagramA Scenario of Micro-Service Flows represents the flows exchanged between certain elements of the micro-service in a given context. The elements represented are: micro-services, IT services, data stores, the access points (service point and request point) and the connections between components.

enumValues.name: FlowAssessmentDiagramCityPlanningsAreas
enumValues.description: Flow Assessment Diagram (City Plannings Areas)For a city planning area, this diagram presents an assessment of flows between its components and or other city planning areas.This assessment is made through the use of channels which list the flows exchanged between applications, and services distributed in the different city planning areas.

enumValues.name: TOGAFOrganizationDecompositionDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Organization Decomposition DiagramAn Organization Decomposition diagram describes the links between actor, roles, and location within an organization tree.An organization map should provide a chain of command of owners and decision-makers in theorganization. Although it is not the intent of the Organization Decomposition diagram to link goal to organization, it should be possible to intuitively link the goals to the stakeholders from the Organization Decomposition diagram.

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram
enumValues.description: Technical Architecture DiagramThis Technical Architecture diagram represents the Technical Architectures and the Technical Data Areas of the described Application Technical Area as well as the techniques used for their communications.

enumValues.name: WorkInstructions
enumValues.description: Work InstructionsThis diagram describes the details of an operation. This operation is broken down into tasks which are performed by the same org-unit as the operation being described.

enumValues.name: ProcessDiagram
enumValues.description: Process DiagramThis diagram shows how the business process is broken down as well as its exchanges with its main partners.

enumValues.name: TechnicalInfrastructureDiagram
enumValues.description: Technical Infrastructure DiagramThis diagram describes a technical infrastructure in terms of communication networks and hardware and software resources.

enumValues.name: ObjectiveRequirementDiagram
enumValues.description: Objective Requirement DiagramThis diagram is used to define the sub-objectives and the requirements contributing to the fulfillmenbt of an objective. These sub-objectives and requirements can be connected to the objects (processes, applications, ...) contributing to their fulfillment.

enumValues.name: ProcessOrg_UnitsDiagram
enumValues.description: Process Org-Units DiagramThis diagram presents Messages exchanged between the Org-Units involved in the Business Process during its execution.

enumValues.name: ApplicationEnvironmentDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Environment DiagramThis diagram presents the exchanges between the application being studied and the main application that use it.

enumValues.name: StateMachineDiagram
enumValues.description: State Machine DiagramA state machine diagram enables description of possible behaviors of an object, depending on the events it experiences during its life cycle.

enumValues.name: TOGAFSoftwareEngineeringDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Software Engineering DiagramThe Software Engineering diagram breaks applications into packages, modules, services, and operations from a development perspective.It enables more detailed impact analysis when planning migration stages, and analyzing opportunities and solutions.It is ideal for application development teams and application management teams when managing complex development environments.

enumValues.name: ServiceInteractionScenarioDiagram
enumValues.description: Service Interaction Scenario DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a scenario enabling determination of interactions between service-oriented items (business services).

enumValues.name: CapabilityStructureDiagram
enumValues.description: Capability Structure DiagramA Capability Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of a Business Capability  and the dependencies between the components.

enumValues.name: Micro_ServiceScenarioSequenceDiagram
enumValues.description: Micro-Service Scenario Sequence DiagramA Micro-Service Scenario Sequence Diagram  describes the exchanges between the micro-service elements, highlighting their chronology. The elements in the scenario are represented in the diagram by lines.

enumValues.name: DeploymentDiagram
enumValues.description: Deployment DiagramThe deployment diagram supplements the component diagram, by providing a view of the system once it is deployed. It enables indication of objects used when implementing the system.

enumValues.name: SiteTreeDiagram
enumValues.description: Site Tree DiagramThis diagram describes a site through a tree diagram of its components.

enumValues.name: Organizational_UnitStructureDiagram
enumValues.description: Organizational-Unit Structure DiagramAn Organizational-Unit Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Org-Unit, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: ApplicationInternalArchitectureDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Internal Architecture DiagramThis diagram details the exchanges between the components (applications and services) involved in the behavior of the application being studied.

enumValues.name: BrokerDiagram
enumValues.description: Broker DiagramThis diagram enables description of the communications (message, event or collaboration) hosted by the broker.This diagram can also contain the connector objects.

enumValues.name: OverviewofObjectivesandProjects
enumValues.description: Overview of Objectives and ProjectsThis diagram describes main strategic projects and their associated objectives.

enumValues.name: SolManProcessDiagram
enumValues.description: SolMan Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a Solman process.

enumValues.name: ResourceArchitectureStructureDiagram
enumValues.description: Resource Architecture Structure DiagramA resource architecture structure diagram displays graphically the first level components of a resource architecture, the access points (service points and communication ports) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: SequenceDiagramUMLTwo
enumValues.description: Sequence Diagram (UML2)The sequence diagram highlights the chronology of messages exchanged between objects participating in the interaction. These objects are represented in the diagram by their lifelines.

enumValues.name: DataDiagram
enumValues.description: Data DiagramDiagram to create data models.

enumValues.name: SchedulingDiagram
enumValues.description: Scheduling DiagramThe Project Scheduling Diagram enables you to describe the sequencing of your organization, architecture, integration or development projects in conjunction with MOKA (MEGA Open Kit Approach).

enumValues.name: ProjectObjectiveandRequirementDiagram
enumValues.description: Project Objective and Requirement DiagramThis diagram is used to define the objectives and requirements of a project. These objectives and requirements can be connected to the objects (processes, applications, ...) contributing to their fulfillment.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionTreeDiagram
enumValues.description: Business Function Tree DiagramThis diagram describes a business function through a tree diagram of its components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFProcessFlowDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Process Flow DiagramThe purpose of the Process Flow diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to the process metamodel entity.Process Flow diagrams show sequential flow of control between activities and may utilize swimlane techniques to represent ownership and realization of process steps. For example, the application that supports a process step may be shown as a swim-lane.In addition to showing a sequence of activity, process flows can also be used to detail the controls that apply to a process, the events that trigger or result from completion of a process, and also the products that are generated from process execution.Process Flow diagrams are useful in elaborating the architecture with subject specialists, as they allow the specialist to describe  how the job is done  for a particular function. Through this process, each process step can become a more fine-grained function and can then in turn be elaborated as a process.

enumValues.name: ServiceArchitectureDiagram
enumValues.description: Service Architecture DiagramThis diagram details the exchanges between the components involved in the behavior of the service.

enumValues.name: FlowAssessmentDiagramBusinessFunctions
enumValues.description: Flow Assessment Diagram (Business Functions)For a business function, this diagram presents an assessment of flows between its components and or other business functionsThis assessment is made through the use of channels which list the flows exchanged between activities (involvement of business functions within business processes).

enumValues.name: InterfaceDiagram
enumValues.description: Interface DiagramAn interface diagram enables precise description of the interfaces of each of the packages with the exterior. It also enables specification of dependency relationships between these packages as well as the classes involved.

enumValues.name: ApplicationEnvironmentReport
enumValues.description: Application Environment ReportReport describing all the environment of an application.

enumValues.name: SequenceDiagram
enumValues.description: Sequence DiagramWith the sequence diagram, it is easier to understand the order of actions over time and the temporal constraints on object interactions.

enumValues.name: OverviewofBusinessFunctions
enumValues.description: Overview of Business FunctionsThis diagram presents an assessment of flows between the enterprise s main business functions.This assessment is made through the use of channels which list the flows exchanged between activities (involvement of business functions within business processes).

enumValues.name: ObjectiveAlignmentDiagram
enumValues.description: Objective Alignment DiagramThe Objective Alignment diagram is used to describe how the objectives involved in a strategic model will be handled in the company through applications, processes, etc.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionViewpoint
enumValues.description: Business Function ViewpointThe Business Function viewpoint shows the main business functions of an organization and their relations in terms of the flows of information, value, or goods between them. Business functions are used to represent the most stable aspects of a company in terms of the primary activities it performs, regardless of organizational changes  or technological developments. Therefore, the business function architecture of companies that operate in the same market often exhibit close similarities. The business function viewpoint thus provides high-level insight in the general operations of the company, and can be used to identify necessary competencies, or to structure an organization according to its main activities.

enumValues.name: OrganizationalProcessTreeDiagram
enumValues.description: Organizational Process Tree DiagramAn Organizational Process Tree Diagram is a diagram showing the hierarchy of Organizational Process.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEnvironmentsandLocationsDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Environments and Locations DiagramThe Environments and Locations diagram depicts which locations host which applications, identifies what technologies and or applications are used at which locations, and finally identifies the locations from which business users typically interact with the applications.This diagram should also show the existence and location of different deployment environments, including non-production environments, such as development and pre production.

enumValues.name: ActivityDecompositionDiagram
enumValues.description: Activity Decomposition DiagramThis diagram describes the decomposition of an activity through a chain of sub-activities. Each sub-activity represents the contribution of a business function within the parent activity.

enumValues.name: ActivityImplementationDiagram
enumValues.description: Activity Implementation DiagramThis diagram describes the implementation of the activity through the procedures of the business process.Each of these procedures is under the responsibility of a specific organizational unit (type structure).

enumValues.name: BusinessCapabilityMapOrg_Unit
enumValues.description: Business Capability Map / Org-UnitDisplays the distribution of applications used by the Org-Unit in the areas of the chosen City Plan.

enumValues.name: BusinessCapabilityMapTechnology
enumValues.description: Business Capability Map / TechnologyDisplays the distribution of applications using a technology in the areas of the chosen city plan.

enumValues.name: ResourceArchitectureTreeDiagram
enumValues.description: Resource Architecture Tree DiagramA resource architecture tree is a diagram showing the hierarchy of resource architectures.

enumValues.name: ApplicationBehaviorViewPointDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Behavior ViewPoint DiagramThe Application Behavior viewpoint describes the internal behavior of an application; e.g., as it realizes one or more application services. This viewpoint is useful in designing the main behavior of applications, or in identifying functional overlap between different applications.

enumValues.name: JobFunctionSheet
enumValues.description: Job Function SheetThis diagram enables the exhaustive description of the Operations performed by the Org-Unit within the different Procedures where it intervenes.

enumValues.name: AppianOrganizationalProcessDiagram
enumValues.description: Appian Organizational Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe an organizational process for Appian.

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram
enumValues.description: Technical Architecture DiagramThis Technical Architecture diagram represents the Technical Architectures and the Technical Data Areas of the described Application System Technical Architecture as well as the techniques used for their communications.

enumValues.name: AppianSystemProcessdiagram
enumValues.description: Appian System Process diagramThis diagram is used to describe a systeml process for Appian.

enumValues.name: EnterprisePhaseTreeDiagram
enumValues.description: Enterprise Phase Tree DiagramAn Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram is a diagram showing the hierarchy of Enterprise Phase.

enumValues.name: BusinessProcessViewpoint
enumValues.description: Business Process ViewpointThe Business Process viewpoint is used to show the high-level structure and composition of one or more business processes. Next to the processes themselves, this viewpoint contains other directly related concepts, such as: - The services a business process offers to the outside world, showing how a process contributes to the realization of the company s products - The assignment of business processes to roles, which gives insight into the responsibilities of the associated actors - The information used by the business process Each of these can be regarded as a  sub-view  of the business process view.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataLifecycleDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Lifecycle DiagramThe Data Lifecycle diagram is an essential part of managing business data throughout its lifecycle from conception until disposal within the constraints of the business process.The data is considered as an entity in its own right, decoupled from business process and activity. Each change in state is represented on the diagram which may include the event or rules that trigger that change in state.The separation of data from process allows common data requirements to be identified which enables resource sharing to be achieved more effectively.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessDiagram
enumValues.description: System Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a system process using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of tasks, the conditioning and the events. Tasks can be assigned to participants that represent applications, IT services or org-units (for interactive tasks).This representation of a process is used to answer the question: how does my system work?

enumValues.name: ValueStreamDiagram
enumValues.description: Value Stream DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a Value Stream, using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of Value Stages, the conditioning and the events. Value Stages can be assigned to participants that represent the skills needed to perform them.This representation of a Value Stream is used to respond to the question: which skill do I need?

enumValues.name: ApplicationCo_operationViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Co-operation Viewpoint DiagramThe Application Co-operation viewpoint describes the relations between applications components in terms of the information flows between them, or in terms of the services they offer and use. This viewpoint is typically used to create an overview of the application landscape of an organization. This viewpoint is also  used to express the (internal) co-operation or orchestration of services that together support the execution of a business process.

enumValues.name: ProductViewPointDiagram
enumValues.description: Product ViewPoint DiagramThe Product viewpoint depicts the value these products offer to the customers or other external parties involved and shows the composition of one or more products in terms of the constituting (business or application) services, and the associated contract(s) or other agreements. It may also be used to show the interfaces (channels) through which this product is offered, and the events associated with the product. A Product viewpoint is typically used in product development to design a product by composing existing services or by identifying which new services have to be created for this product, given the value a customer expects from it. It may then serve as input for business process architects and others that  need to design the processes and ICT realizing these products.

enumValues.name: ClassDiagram
enumValues.description: Class DiagramA class diagram is used to represent the static structure of a system, particularly the types of objects manipulated in the system, their internal structure, and the relationships between them.

enumValues.name: TOGAFGoalObjectiveServiceDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service DiagramThe purpose of a Goal Objective Service diagram is to define the ways in which a service contributes to the achievement of a business vision or strategy.Services are associated with the drivers, goals, objectives, and measures that they support, allowing the enterprise to understand which services contribute to similar aspects of business performance. The Goal Objective Service diagram also provides qualitative input on what constitutes high performance for a particular service.

enumValues.name: StateDiagram
enumValues.description: State DiagramA state diagram describes the evolution over time of an object of a certain class, and shows its behavior in response to interactions with other objects (internal or external to the studied system) in its environment.

enumValues.name: ApplicationStructureDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Structure DiagramAn Application Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Application, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataSecurityDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Security DiagramData is considered as an asset to the enterprise and data security simply means ensuring that enterprise data is not compromised and that access to it is suitably controlled.The purpose of the Data Security diagram is to depict which actor (person, organization, or system) can access which enterprise data. This relationship can be shown in a matrix form between two objects or can be shown as a mapping.The diagram can also be used to demonstrate compliance with data privacy laws and other applicable regulations (HIPAA, SOX, etc). This diagram should also consider any trust implications where an enterprise s partners or other parties may have access to the company s systems, such as an outsourced situation where information may be managed by other people and may even be hosted in a different country.

enumValues.name: ConceptualCommunicationModel
enumValues.description: Conceptual Communication ModelThis diagram is used in the Merise formalism to describe the exchange of information between business areas or activities in the company.

enumValues.name: FlowModel
enumValues.description: Flow ModelThis diagram is used in the Merise framework to describe the exchange of information between organizational units (organizational view).

enumValues.name: ConceptualDataModel
enumValues.description: Conceptual Data ModelThis diagram is used in the Merise methodology to describe the data model of a business function or an activity using entities and relationships.

enumValues.name: OrganizationalDataModel
enumValues.description: Organizational Data ModelThis diagram is used to describe the sub-set of data used  in a specific context in the organization.

enumValues.name: ConceptualProcessModel
enumValues.description: Conceptual Process ModelThis diagram is used in the Merise methodology to describe the process model of a business function or an activity using operations and messages.

enumValues.name: Flowchart
enumValues.description: FlowchartThis diagram is used to describe the procedure as a sequence of operations performed by org-units (type function).

enumValues.name: ConceptualTree
enumValues.description: Conceptual TreeThe conceptual tree, in the Merise framework,  allow resuming conceptual decomposition of business functions, activities and operations.

enumValues.name: OrganizationalChart
enumValues.description: Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: ApplicationArchitectureDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Architecture DiagramAn Application Architecture Diagram describes the software environment of an application, a site, an org-unit, or for the entire company

enumValues.name: ToolBranchingModel
enumValues.description: Tool Branching ModelThis diagram is used to describe the branchings between interactive services grouped to provide a specific service.

enumValues.name: InteractiveToolModel
enumValues.description: Interactive Tool ModelThis diagram describes the logical sequence of the screens of an interactive service.

enumValues.name: RelationalDiagram
enumValues.description: Relational DiagramA relational diagram describes a database: It represents the physical data structures used by programs.

enumValues.name: CodasylLogicalDataModel
enumValues.description: Codasyl Logical Data ModelThis diagram is used to describe a logical data model in Codasyl formalism with records and sets.

enumValues.name: LogicalDataModel
enumValues.description: Logical Data ModelThis diagram is used to describe a logical data model with tables and records.

enumValues.name: UseCaseDiagram
enumValues.description: Use Case DiagramUse case diagrams show actors and use cases together with their relationships. The use cases represent functionality of a system as manifested to external interactors with the system or the classifier.

enumValues.name: ApplicationTree
enumValues.description: Application TreeThis diagram describes an application through a tree diagram of its components (sub-applications and services).

enumValues.name: ObjectLifeCycle
enumValues.description: Object Life CycleThis diagram is used to describe the possible states of an object and the possible transitions between thes states.

enumValues.name: NonInteractiveToolModel
enumValues.description: Non Interactive Tool ModelThis diagram is used to describe a non interactive service (batch).

enumValues.name: AuthorizationTree
enumValues.description: Authorization TreeThis diagram is used to specify user autorization hierarchy.

enumValues.name: BatchPlanningDiagram
enumValues.description: Batch Planning DiagramBatch Planning diagram describes automatic processing sequencing.

enumValues.name: ChainModel
enumValues.description: Chain ModelThe Chain Diagram enables representation of a chain (job) in terms of steps (processing stages).

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram
enumValues.description: Technical Architecture DiagramThe Technical Architecture Diagram (TAD) focuses on the hardware architecture needed to run the software. This type of diagram provides a detailed description of the technical architecture: network management, information flows, routing, and so on.The TAD also allows you to choose the correct hardware configuration for your applications and databases, plus the networks used to exchange information.

enumValues.name: BusinessServiceTreeDiagram
enumValues.description: Business Service Tree DiagramA Business Service Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of Business Services.

enumValues.name: TOGAFPlatformDecompositionDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Platform Decomposition DiagramThe Platform Decomposition diagram depicts the technology platform that supports the operations of the Information Systems Architecture. The diagram covers all aspects of the infrastructure platform and provides an overview of the enterprise s technology platform. The diagram can be expanded to map the technology platform to appropriate application components within a specific functional or process area. This diagram may show details of specification, such as product versions, number of CPUs, etc. or simply could be an informal  eye-chart  providing an overview of the technical environment.

enumValues.name: CommunicationDiagram
enumValues.description: Communication DiagramCommunication Diagrams focus on the interaction between lifelines where the architecture of the internal structure and how this corresponds with the message passing is central. The sequencing of messages is given through a sequence numbering scheme.The communication diagram is a simplified representation of the sequence diagram, concentrating on message exchanges between objects within an interaction.

enumValues.name: ObjectiveandRequirementdiagram
enumValues.description: Objective and Requirement diagramThe objective and requirement diagram explains the connection between elements concerned by an objective or constrained by a requirement and elements that contribute to achievement of an objective or satisfaction of a requirement.

enumValues.name: ActivityDiagramUMLTwo
enumValues.description: Activity Diagram (UML2)An activity diagram describes the sequence and conditions coordinating actions as well as the object flows exchanged during processing.These actions can be initiated because other actions finish executing, because objects and data become available, or because events occur external to the flow.

enumValues.name: ApplicationStructureViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Application Structure Viewpoint DiagramThe Application Structure viewpoint shows the  structure of one or more applications or components. This viewpoint is useful in designing or understanding the main structure of applications or components and the associated  data; e.g., to break down the structure of the system under construction, or to identify legacy application components that are suitable for migration integration.

enumValues.name: InteractionOverviewDiagram
enumValues.description: Interaction Overview DiagramInteraction Overview Diagrams define interactions through a variant of activity diagrams in a way that promotes overview of the control flow. They focus on the overview of the flow of control where the nodes are interactions or  interaction uses. The interaction overview diagram describes sequences possible between scenarios previously identified in the form of sequence diagrams.

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemEnvironmentDiagram
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Environment DiagramA Logical Application System Environment Diagram describes the interactions between a logical application system and its external partners in a specific context.

enumValues.name: Org_UnitOrganizationalChart
enumValues.description: Org-Unit Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: BusinessCapabilityMapBusinessProcess
enumValues.description: Business Capability Map / Business ProcessDisplays the distribution of applications who participated in the process in the areas of the chosen City Plan.

enumValues.name: SystemImpactDiagram
enumValues.description: System Impact DiagramThis diagram is used to explicitly model and show impacts between elements in the scope of an UML package and other objects.

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationCommunicationDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application Communication DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEventDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Event DiagramThe purpose of the Event diagram is to depict the relationship between events and process.Certain events - such as arrival of certain information (e.g., customer submits sales order) or a certain point in time (e.g., end of fiscal quarter) - cause work and certain actions need to be under taken within the business. These are often referred to as  business events  or simply  events  and are considered as triggers for a process. It is important to note that the event has to trigger a process and generate a business response or result.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessTreeDiagram
enumValues.description: System Process Tree DiagramA System Process Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of  System Processs.

enumValues.name: BusinessProcessEnvironmentDiagram
enumValues.description: Business Process Environment DiagramThis diagram presents exhanges between the business process, its client, as well as its main suppliers and partners.The client is represented as an external entity or and org-unit. Other participants can be external entities, org-units, roles or other business processes.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataDisseminationDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Dissemination DiagramThe purpose of the Data Dissemination diagram is to show the relationship between data entity, business service, and application components. The diagram shows how the logical entities are to be physically realized by application components. This allows effective sizing to be carried out and the IT footprint to be refined. Moreover, by assigning business value to data, an indication of the business criticality of application components can be gained.Additionally, the diagram may show data replication and system ownership of the master reference for data. In this instance, it can show two copies and the master-copy relationship between them. This diagram can include services; that is, services encapsulate data and they reside in an application, or services that reside on an application and access data encapsulated within the application.

enumValues.name: WorkflowDiagram
enumValues.description: Workflow DiagramThis diagram enables definition of the sequence of steps (operations) that constitute the workflow, as well as the implementing resource associated with each of these steps (org-unit, application).

enumValues.name: TOGAFFunctionalDecompositionDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Functional Decomposition DiagramThe purpose of the Functional Decomposition diagram is to show on a single page the capabilities of an organization that are relevant to the consideration of an architecture. By examining the capabilities of an organization from a functional perspective, it is possible to quickly develop models of what the organization does without being dragged into extended debate on how the organization does it.Once a basic Functional Decomposition diagram has been developed, it becomes possible to layer heat-maps on top of this diagram to show scope and decisions. For example, thecapabilities to be implemented in different phases of a change program.

enumValues.name: RiskDiagram
enumValues.description: Risk DiagramThis diagram is used to describe where a risk can occur, its impacts and how it can be prevented.

enumValues.name: StateConceptStructureDiagram
enumValues.description: State Concept Structure DiagramThe diagram of this MetaAttributeValue is to describe a concept state structure. This diagram is a same than concept structure diagram.

enumValues.name: ReportDiagram
enumValues.description: Report DiagramThis diagram is used to implement diagrams built dynamically during the execution of an analysis, especially bubble charts.

enumValues.name: ServiceTaxonomyDiagram
enumValues.description: Service Taxonomy DiagramThis diagram describes the taxonomy of the service definition through a tree diagram of its specializations and generalizations.

enumValues.name: Cause_and_EffectDiagram
enumValues.description: Cause-and-Effect DiagramThe cause-and-effect diagram (also called Ishikawa diagram or fishbone diagram) is a tool that enables identification of the possible causes of an observed effect and therefore determination of a means of solving the problems.

enumValues.name: GeneralOrganizationalChart
enumValues.description: General Organizational ChartThis diagram provides a general description of the enterprise management structureIt enables description of both hierarchical and functional dependencies.

enumValues.name: TimelineDiagram
enumValues.description: Timeline DiagramThe Timeline diagram presents the sequance of key timespots of an organization or a project. A timespot can be represented by a fixed date or a limited time priod.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionStructureDiagram
enumValues.description: Business Function Structure DiagramA Operational Node Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of a Business Function, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEnterpriseManageabilityDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Enterprise Manageability DiagramThe Enterprise Manageability diagram shows how one or more applications interact with application and technology components that support operational management of a solution.This diagram is really a filter on the Application Communication diagram, specifically for enterprise management class software.Analysis can reveal duplication and gaps, and opportunities in the IT service management operation of an organization.

enumValues.name: SequenceDiagramSBP
enumValues.description: Sequence Diagram (SBP)With the sequence diagram, it is easier to understand the order of actions over time and the temporal constraints on object interactions.

enumValues.name: PackageDiagram
enumValues.description: Package DiagramA package diagram divides the classes into different packages, in order to partition the work involved in specification and development. A class should only appear in a single package. Dividing into packages is generally carried out so as to minimise interactions between different packages.

enumValues.name: CollaborationDiagram
enumValues.description: Collaboration DiagramA Collaboration is used for describing the realization of an operation or a classifier.

enumValues.name: TOGAFCommunicationsEngineeringDiagram
enumValues.description: TOGAF Communications Engineering DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: InfrastructureUsageViewPointDiagram
enumValues.description: Infrastructure Usage ViewPoint DiagramThe Infrastructure Usage viewpoint shows how applications are supported by the software and hardware infrastructure: the infrastructure services are delivered by the devices; system software and networks are provided to the applications. This viewpoint plays an important role in the analysis of performance and scalability, since it relates the physical infrastructure to the logical world of applications. It is very useful in determining the performance and quality requirements on the infrastructure based on the demands of the various applications that use it.

enumValues.name: OverviewofBusinessProcesses
enumValues.description: Overview of Business ProcessesThis diagram presents the enterprise s main business processes and their client.

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemStructureDiagram
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Structure DiagramDiagram describing the internal structure of a Logical Application System, its provided or requested services, its conducted processes, its components and their interactions as well as end-users and their interactions with components.

enumValues.name: TechnicalFunctionalityDiagram
enumValues.description: Technical Functionality DiagramA Technical Functionality Diagram is a representation of the set of functionalities with their dependencies that, jointly, define the scope of an equipment item (hardware or software) corresponding to the Technical Functionality.

enumValues.name: TechnicalFunctionalityMapDiagram

enumValues.name: LayeredViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Layered Viewpoint DiagramThe Layered viewpoint pictures several layers and aspects of an enterprise architecture in one diagram. There are two categories of layers, namely  dedicated layers and  service layers. The layers are the result of the use of the  grouping  relation for a natural partitioning of the entire set of objects and relations that belong to a model. The infrastructure, the application, the process, and the actors roles layers belong to the first category. The structural principle behind a fully layered viewpoint is that each dedicated  layer exposes, by means of the  realization  relation a layer of services, which are further on   used by  the next dedicated layer. Thus, we can easily separate the internal structure and organization of a dedicated layer from its externally observable behavior expressed as the service layer  that the dedicated layer realizes. The order, number, or nature of these layers are not fixed, but in general a (more or less) complete and natural layering of an ArchiMate model will contain the succession of layers depicted in the example given below. However, this example is by no means intended to be prescriptive. The main goal of the Layered viewpoint is to provide overview in one diagram. Furthermore, this viewpoint can be used as support for impact of change analysis and performance analysis or for extending the service portfolio.

enumValues.name: BusinessProcessDiagram
enumValues.description: Business Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a structure of the business of the company. It presents product or service offerings, the composition of business processes that produce them and their implementation by functional, organizational or system processes. This diagram uses a subset of the BPMN notation.

enumValues.name: ArtifactAssemblyDiagram

enumValues.name: InformationStructureViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Information Structure Viewpoint DiagramThe Information Structure viewpoint is comparable to the traditional information models created in the development of almost any information system. It shows the structure of the informationused in the enterprise or in a specific business process or application, in terms of data types or (object-oriented) class structures. Furthermore, it may show how the information at the business level is represented at the application level in the form of the data structures used there, and how these are then mapped onto the underlying infrastructure; e.g., by means of a database schema.

enumValues.name: BusinessProcessCo_operationViewpointDiagram
enumValues.description: Business Process Co-operation Viewpoint DiagramThe Business Process Co-operation viewpoint is used to show the relations of one or more business processes with each other and or with their environment. It can both be used to create a high-level design of business processes within their context and to provide an operational manager responsible for one or more such processes with insight into their dependencies. Important aspects of business process co-operation are: - Causal relations between the main business processes of the enterprise - Mapping of business processes onto business functions - Realization of services by business processes - Use of shared data - Execution of a business process by the same roles or actors Each of these can be regarded as a  sub-view  of the business process co-operation view.

properties.name: RecoveryPointObjectiveRPO
properties.description: The Recovery Point Objective (RPO) determines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time.Four levels of RPO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable data loss is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable data loss is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable data loss is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable data loss is days)

properties.name: RecoveryTimeObjectiveRTO
properties.description: The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online. This covers, for example, restore data from back-up or fix of a failure.Four levels of RTO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is days)

properties.name: WorkRecoveryTimeWRT
properties.description: The Work Recovery Time (WRT) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity. This could be, for example, checking the databases and logs, making sure the applications or services are running and are available.Four levels of WRT need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is days)

properties.name: MaximumTolerableDowntimeMTD
properties.description: Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) determines the maximum time a business can tolerate the absence or unavailability of a particular application.Downtime consists of two elements, the Recovery Time Objective and the Work Recovery Time: MTD = RTO + WRTMTD level will be calculated automatically according to RTO and WRT levels, it cannot be modified manually.-	Critical (maximum tolerable downtime is seconds)-	Serious (maximum tolerable downtime is minutes)-	Significant (maximum tolerable downtime is hours)-	Minor (maximum tolerable downtime is days)
